V'''Anthony Maurice (Tony) Honoré''' (born 30 March 1921)<ref>{{cite book|title=Jahrbuch der Bayerischen Akademie der Wissenschaften|year=1987|publisher=Bayerische Akademie der Wissenschaften|isbn=9783769679762|page=49|language=German}}</ref>  is a British [[lawyer]] and [[jurist]], known for his work on [[ownership]], [[causation (law)|causation]] and [[Roman law]].<ref name="Gardner">John Gardner [http://users.ox.ac.uk/~lawf0081/pdfs/honore.pdf ''Tony Honoré as Teacher and Mentor: A Personal Memoir'']; read April 1st, 2014.</ref>\u000a\u000aHonoré was born in [[London]] but was brought up in [[South Africa]]. He served in the army during the [[Second World War]] and was severely wounded in the [[First Battle of El Alamein|Battle of Alamein]]. After the war he continued his studies at [[New College, Oxford]], and he has lived and taught in [[Oxford, England|Oxford]] for the last fifty-five years, including periods as a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Fellow]] of [[The Queen's College, Oxford|The Queen's College]] and then of New College.<ref name="AllSouls">Profile of [http://www.all-souls.ox.ac.uk/people.php?personid=150 Tony Honré] All Souls College website, Oxford; read April 1st, 2014.</ref> Between 1971 and 1988 he was [[Regius Professor of Civil Law (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Civil Law at Oxford]] and a Fellow of [[All Souls College, Oxford]];<ref name="OxfordProfile">Profile of [https://www.law.ox.ac.uk/profile/hornorea Tony Honoré] University of Oxford website, read April 1st, 2014.</ref><ref name="SKU 978-1-920025-38-0">Daniel Visser and Max Loubser (2011) ''[http://www.siberink.co.za/p978-1-920025-38-0/Thinking-about-Law-Essays-for-Tony-Honore.aspx Thinking about Law: Essays for Tony Honore]''; Siber Ink, Westlake (South Africa). read April 1st, 2014.</ref> though retired from his Chair, he teaches seminars in Jurisprudence for the [[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]] jointly with [[John Gardner (law)|John Gardner]].\u000a\u000aHonoré was a close associate of [[H. L. A. Hart]]. They jointly wrote ''Causation in the Law'' (Oxford, 1st ed. 1959, 2nd 1985) in 1953-8 and Honoré had some influence on Hart's ''The Concept of Law'' (Oxford, 1st ed. 1961, 2nd 1994). A number of his philosophical papers are collected in ''Making Law Bind'' (Oxford, 1987) and ''Responsibility and Fault'' (Oxford, 1999) and his contributions to legal philosophy and Roman law, which range widely, include sixteen books and more than a hundred articles published over the last six decades.\u000a\u000aHonoré is an honorary [[Queen's Counsel|Q.C.]] and Bencher of [[Lincoln's Inn]], a member of the [[British Academy|British]] and [[Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities|Bavarian Academies]] and of the International Academy of Comparative Law. In South Africa, where he made a contribution to the setting up of the new [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]] in 1995, his standing has been recognised by the award of honorary degrees from the Universities of [[University of South Africa|South Africa]], [[Stellenbosch University|Stellenbosch]] and [[University of Cape Town|Cape Town]]. He has delivered the Hamlyn lectures (1982),<ref>''The Quest for security: Employees, Tenants, Wives'', Tony Honoré [http://socialsciences.exeter.ac.uk/media/universityofexeter/schoolofhumanitiesandsocialsciences/law/pdfs/The_Quest_for_Security_Employees_Tenants_Wives_1.pdf]</ref> the Blackstone and H. L. A. Hart lectures, the J. H. Gray lectures at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and the Maccabaean lecture in Jurisprudence at the British Academy. Three [[Festschrift]]en have been published in his honour.\u000a\u000a* Neil MacCormick and Peter Birks (eds., 1985) ''The Legal Mind: Essays for Tony Honoré'';<ref name="Festschrift65">Neil MacCormick and Peter Birks (Eds., 1985) ''The Legal Mind: Essays for Tony Honoré''; Claredons Press, Oxford. ISBN 978-0198761969</ref>\u000a* Peter Cane and John Gardner (eds., 2001) ''Relating to Responsibility: Essays in Honor of Tony Honoré on his 80th  Birthday''.<ref name="Festschrift80">Peter Cane and John Gardner (Eds., 2001) ''Relating to Responsibility: Essays in Honor of Tony Honoré on his 80th  Birthday''; Oxford: Hart Publishing Co., ISBN 1-84113-210-1</ref>\u000a* Daniel Visser and Max Loubser (eds., 2011) ''Thinking about Law: Essays for Tony Honore'';<ref name="SKU 978-1-920025-38-0"/>\u000a\u000a==List of publications==\u000a;Books\u000a* ''Gaius: a biography'' (Oxford, 1962) \u000a* ''Tribonian'' (London, 1978) \u000a* ''Sex Law in England'' (London: Duckworth, 1978) \u000a* ''Emperor and Lawyers: with a paligenesia of third-century imperial rescripts 193-305 AD'' (London, 1st ed. 1981; Oxford, 2nd ed. 1994) \u000a* ''Ulpian: pioneer of human rights'' (Oxford, 1st ed. 1982; 2nd ed. 2002) \u000a* ''The Quest for Security: Employees, Tenants, Wives'' (London: Stevens, 1982) \u000a* ''Causation in the Law'' (Oxford, 1st ed. 1959; 2nd 1985) - with [[H. L. A. Hart]] \u000a* ''Making Law Bind'' (Oxford, 1987)\u000a* ''Concordance to the Digest Jurists'' (Oxford: OMP, 1980) - with J. Menner\u000a* ''About Law: an introduction'' (Oxford, 1995)\u000a* ''Law in the Crisis of the Empire 379-455 AD: the Theodosian dynasty and its quaestors'' (Oxford, 1998)\u000a* ''Responsibility and Fault'' (Oxford, 1999)\u000a* ''Justinian's Digest: character and compilation'' (Oxford, 2010)\u000a\u000a;Articles\u000a* "Responsibility and luck: the moral basis of strict liability" (1988) 104 ''Law Quarterly Review'' 530\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://users.ox.ac.uk/~alls0079/ Tony Honoré's web site]. Includes several online papers and brief biographical details.\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Honore, Tony}}\u000a[[Category:1921 births]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of law]]\u000a[[Category:British lawyers]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of New College, Oxford]]\u000a[[Category: